{"type":"message","id":"03c86114","parentId":"4165478c","timestamp":"2026-03-18T01:19:06.153Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-be8a558bd16540a6b1277a5e06eb4984","toolName":"memory_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 399,\n      \"endLine\": 472,\n      \"score\": 0.704022827744484,\n      \"snippet\": \"\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))\\n\\n    if title:\\n        ax.set_title(title)\\n    else:\\n        ax.set_title(f\\\"Generation {generation_num}\\\")\\n\\n    ax.imshow(grid, cmap='binary', interpolation='nearest')\\n    ax.axis('off')\\n    plt.tight_layout()\\n    plt.show()\\n\\ndef compare_patterns(patterns_dict):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Display multiple patterns side-by-side.\\n\\n    Args:\\n        patterns_dict: {name: grid} dictionary\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    n = len(patterns_dict)\\n    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, n, figsize=(4*n, 4))\\n\\n    if n == 1:\\n        axes = [axes]\\n\\n    for ax, (name, grid) in zip(axes, patterns_dict.items()):\\n        ax.set_title(name)\\n        ax.imshow(grid, cmap='binary', interpolation='nearest\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L399-L472\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L399-L472\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 511,\n      \"endLine\": 563,\n      \"score\": 0.6492069244384766,\n      \"snippet\": \"birth = ttnn.logical_and(\\n        ttnn.logical_or(ttnn.eq(neighbors, 3.0), ttnn.eq(neighbors, 6.0)),\\n        ttnn.eq(grid, 0.0)\\n    )\\n\\n    survival = ttnn.logical_and(\\n        ttnn.logical_or(ttnn.eq(neighbors, 2.0), ttnn.eq(neighbors, 3.0)),\\n        ttnn.eq(grid, 1.0)\\n    )\\n\\n    return ttnn.to_float(ttnn.logical_or(birth, survival))\\n```\\n\\n### 3. Multi-Color Variants\\nTrack cell \\\"age\\\" or \\\"species\\\":\\n\\n```python\\ndef step_with_age(self, grid):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Cells have age (color) that increases each generation.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    next_grid = self.step(grid)\\n\\n    # Increment age of surviving cells\\n    aged = ttnn.add(grid, 1.0)\\n    aged = ttnn.where(ttnn.eq(next_grid, 1.0), aged, 0.0)\\n\\n    return aged\\n```\\n\\n### 4.\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L511-L563\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L511-L563\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 1,\n      \"endLine\": 57,\n      \"score\": 0.6299433410167694,\n      \"snippet\": \"---\\nid: cookbook-game-of-life\\ntitle: \\\"Recipe 1: Conway's Game of Life\\\"\\ndescription: >-\\n  Build Conway's Game of Life using TTNN parallel tile computing. Learn convolution operations, cellular automata, and visual output generation. Includes classic patterns: gliders, blinkers, and the famous Gosper Glider Gun!\\ncategory: cookbook\\ntags:\\n  - ttnn\\n  - convolution\\n  - cellular-automata\\n  - visualization\\nsupportedHardware:\\n  - n150\\n  - n300\\n  - t3k\\n  - p100\\n  - p150\\n  - p300\\n  - galaxy\\nstatus: validated\\nvalidatedOn:\\n  - n150\\n  - p300\\nestimatedMinutes: 30\\n---\\n\\n# Recipe 1: Conway's Game of Life 🎮\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nConway's Game of Life is a cellular automaton where cells evolve based on simple rules:\\n-\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L1-L57\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L1-L57\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 48,\n      \"endLine\": 105,\n      \"score\": 0.6228457570075989,\n      \"snippet\": \"[![Game of Life Animation](/assets/img/game_of_life_preview.png)](https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-vscode-toolkit/blob/main/assets/img/game_of_life.gif)\\n\\n*Classic \\\"Gosper Glider Gun\\\" pattern generating infinite gliders on TT hardware. Simple convolution rules create complex emergent behavior.*\\n\\n[View full animation →](https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-vscode-toolkit/blob/main/assets/img/game_of_life.gif)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Deploy the Project\\n\\n[📦 Deploy All Cookbook Projects](command:tenstorrent.createCookbookProjects)\\n\\nThis creates the project in `~/tt-scratchpad/cookbook/game_of_life/`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Project Structure\\n\\n```text\\n~/tt-scratchpad/cookbook/game_of_life/\\n├── game_of_life.py       # Core TTNN\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L48-L105\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L48-L105\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 107,\n      \"endLine\": 150,\n      \"score\": 0.6199801623821258,\n      \"snippet\": \"| Game of Life | Convolution | YOLO v10-v12, SegFormer |\\n| Audio Processor | Spectrograms | Whisper speech recognition |\\n| Mandelbrot | Parallel pixel processing | Stable Diffusion 3.5 |\\n| Image Filters | 2D convolutions | ResNet50, MobileNetV2, ViT |\\n| Particle Life | N² algorithms | Physics simulation, pairwise interactions |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What You'll Learn\\n\\nAfter completing the cookbook, you'll have:\\n\\n- ✅ **5 complete, working projects** you built yourself\\n- ✅ **Deep understanding of TTNN operations** (convolution, FFT, parallel compute)\\n- ✅ **Experience with parallel tile computing** optimized for TT hardware\\n- ✅ **Foundation for production applications** and model bring-up\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Next Step\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md#L107-L150\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md#L107-L150\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 177,\n      \"endLine\": 226,\n      \"score\": 0.5653255119919777,\n      \"snippet\": \"│\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L177-L226\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L177-L226\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 119,\n      \"endLine\": 166,\n      \"score\": 0.49859619140624994,\n      \"snippet\": \"learning_rate: 0.0001            # Standard for fine-tuning\\n  weight_decay: 0.01\\n  use_moreh_adamw: true\\n  use_kahan_summation: false\\n  use_clip_grad_norm: true\\n  clip_grad_norm_max_norm: 1.0\\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 4   # Effective batch: 8 * 4 = 32\\n  eval_every: 50                   # Validate every 50 steps\\n  model_save_interval: 100         # Checkpoint every 100 steps\\n  tokenizer_type: \\\"bpe\\\"\\n  checkpoint_dir: \\\"checkpoints\\\"\\n  model_config: \\\"model_configs/model.yaml\\\"\\n\\n  # Logging configuration (tt-blacksmith pattern)\\n  log_level: \\\"INFO\\\"\\n  use_wandb: false                 # Optional experiment tracking\\n  wandb_project: \\\"my-training\\\"\\n  wandb_run_name: \\\"n150-experiment\\\"\\n\\n  # Checkpoi\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md#L119-L166\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md#L119-L166\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 737,\n      \"endLine\": 793,\n      \"score\": 0.4973596394062042,\n      \"snippet\": \"--model_path ~/tt-metal/tt-train/checkpoints/shakespeare_stage3.pkl_final.pkl \\\\\\n  --max_new_tokens 50 \\\\\\n  --temperature 0.8\\n\\n# Stage 4 (fluent!) - Expect high quality\\npython train_nanogpt.py \\\\\\n  --prompt \\\"ROMEO:\\\" \\\\\\n  --model_path ~/tt-metal/tt-train/checkpoints/shakespeare_final.pkl_final.pkl \\\\\\n  --max_new_tokens 50 \\\\\\n  --temperature 0.8\\n```\\n\\n**This demonstrates hierarchical learning visually!** 🎓\\n\\n---\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Step 8: Experiment with Temperature & Prompts 🎯\\n\\nNow that you have trained models, explore how temperature affects creativity!\\n\\n### Understanding Temperature\\n\\n**Temperature** controls output creativity:\\n- **0.1** = Very deterministic (greedy-like, repetitive)\\n- **0.5** = Balanced,\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md#L737-L793\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md#L737-L793\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 291,\n      \"endLine\": 351,\n      \"score\": 0.4792765527963638,\n      \"snippet\": \"- **Memory-bandwidth advantage**\\n\\n**This is why Tenstorrent is good at AI workloads** - lots of reuse of data in L1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Part 4: Hands-On - Measuring Memory Performance\\n\\nLet's write experiments to measure latency and bandwidth.\\n\\n### Experiment Setup\\n\\nWe'll create two programs:\\n1. **Latency test:** Access single elements (worst case for cache)\\n2. **Bandwidth test:** Access large sequential chunks (best case for cache)\\n\\n### Build the Memory Hierarchy Example\\n\\nFirst, let's build a custom example:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd ~/tt-metal\\n./build_metal.sh --build-programming-examples\\n```\\n\\n[🔨 Build Examples](command:tenstorrent.buildProgrammingExamples)\\n\\n### Experiment 1: Latency - Random Access\\n\\n**Scenario:*\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L291-L351\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L291-L351\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"path\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct5-multi-device-training.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 128,\n      \"endLine\": 199,\n      \"score\": 0.44390186965465545,\n      \"snippet\": \"- ⚠️ You only have N150 (single chip)\\n- ⚠️ Debugging training issues (simpler to debug on 1 device)\\n- ⚠️ Very small datasets (overhead not worth it)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Configuration Changes for DDP\\n\\n### N150 (Single Device) - Baseline\\n\\n```yaml\\ntraining_config:\\n  batch_size: 8\\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 4\\n  # Effective batch: 8 × 4 = 32\\n\\ndevice_config:\\n  enable_ddp: False\\n  mesh_shape: [1, 1]               # 1 device\\n```\\n\\n### N300 (Dual Chips) - DDP Enabled\\n\\n```yaml\\ntraining_config:\\n  batch_size: 16                   # 2x larger (split across devices)\\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 2   # Reduced (same effective batch)\\n  # Effective batch: 16 × 2 = 32 (same as N150!)\\n\\ndevice_config:\\n  enable_ddp: Tr\\n\\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct5-multi-device-training.md#L128-L199\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct5-multi-device-training.md#L128-L199\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"provider\": \"local\",\n  \"model\": \"hf:ggml-org/embeddinggemma-300m-qat-q8_0-GGUF/embeddinggemma-300m-qat-Q8_0.gguf\",\n  \"citations\": \"auto\",\n  \"mode\": \"hybrid\"\n}"}],"details":{"results":[{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md","startLine":399,"endLine":472,"score":0.704022827744484,"snippet":"\"\"\"\n    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))\n\n    if title:\n        ax.set_title(title)\n    else:\n        ax.set_title(f\"Generation {generation_num}\")\n\n    ax.imshow(grid, cmap='binary', interpolation='nearest')\n    ax.axis('off')\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.show()\n\ndef compare_patterns(patterns_dict):\n    \"\"\"\n    Display multiple patterns side-by-side.\n\n    Args:\n        patterns_dict: {name: grid} dictionary\n    \"\"\"\n    n = len(patterns_dict)\n    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, n, figsize=(4*n, 4))\n\n    if n == 1:\n        axes = [axes]\n\n    for ax, (name, grid) in zip(axes, patterns_dict.items()):\n        ax.set_title(name)\n        ax.imshow(grid, cmap='binary', interpolation='nearest\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L399-L472","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L399-L472"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md","startLine":511,"endLine":563,"score":0.6492069244384766,"snippet":"birth = ttnn.logical_and(\n        ttnn.logical_or(ttnn.eq(neighbors, 3.0), ttnn.eq(neighbors, 6.0)),\n        ttnn.eq(grid, 0.0)\n    )\n\n    survival = ttnn.logical_and(\n        ttnn.logical_or(ttnn.eq(neighbors, 2.0), ttnn.eq(neighbors, 3.0)),\n        ttnn.eq(grid, 1.0)\n    )\n\n    return ttnn.to_float(ttnn.logical_or(birth, survival))\n```\n\n### 3. Multi-Color Variants\nTrack cell \"age\" or \"species\":\n\n```python\ndef step_with_age(self, grid):\n    \"\"\"Cells have age (color) that increases each generation.\"\"\"\n    next_grid = self.step(grid)\n\n    # Increment age of surviving cells\n    aged = ttnn.add(grid, 1.0)\n    aged = ttnn.where(ttnn.eq(next_grid, 1.0), aged, 0.0)\n\n    return aged\n```\n\n### 4.\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L511-L563","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L511-L563"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md","startLine":1,"endLine":57,"score":0.6299433410167694,"snippet":"---\nid: cookbook-game-of-life\ntitle: \"Recipe 1: Conway's Game of Life\"\ndescription: >-\n  Build Conway's Game of Life using TTNN parallel tile computing. Learn convolution operations, cellular automata, and visual output generation. Includes classic patterns: gliders, blinkers, and the famous Gosper Glider Gun!\ncategory: cookbook\ntags:\n  - ttnn\n  - convolution\n  - cellular-automata\n  - visualization\nsupportedHardware:\n  - n150\n  - n300\n  - t3k\n  - p100\n  - p150\n  - p300\n  - galaxy\nstatus: validated\nvalidatedOn:\n  - n150\n  - p300\nestimatedMinutes: 30\n---\n\n# Recipe 1: Conway's Game of Life 🎮\n\n## Overview\n\nConway's Game of Life is a cellular automaton where cells evolve based on simple rules:\n-\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L1-L57","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L1-L57"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md","startLine":48,"endLine":105,"score":0.6228457570075989,"snippet":"[![Game of Life Animation](/assets/img/game_of_life_preview.png)](https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-vscode-toolkit/blob/main/assets/img/game_of_life.gif)\n\n*Classic \"Gosper Glider Gun\" pattern generating infinite gliders on TT hardware. Simple convolution rules create complex emergent behavior.*\n\n[View full animation →](https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-vscode-toolkit/blob/main/assets/img/game_of_life.gif)\n\n---\n\n## Deploy the Project\n\n[📦 Deploy All Cookbook Projects](command:tenstorrent.createCookbookProjects)\n\nThis creates the project in `~/tt-scratchpad/cookbook/game_of_life/`.\n\n---\n\n## Project Structure\n\n```text\n~/tt-scratchpad/cookbook/game_of_life/\n├── game_of_life.py       # Core TTNN\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L48-L105","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-game-of-life.md#L48-L105"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md","startLine":107,"endLine":150,"score":0.6199801623821258,"snippet":"| Game of Life | Convolution | YOLO v10-v12, SegFormer |\n| Audio Processor | Spectrograms | Whisper speech recognition |\n| Mandelbrot | Parallel pixel processing | Stable Diffusion 3.5 |\n| Image Filters | 2D convolutions | ResNet50, MobileNetV2, ViT |\n| Particle Life | N² algorithms | Physics simulation, pairwise interactions |\n\n---\n\n## What You'll Learn\n\nAfter completing the cookbook, you'll have:\n\n- ✅ **5 complete, working projects** you built yourself\n- ✅ **Deep understanding of TTNN operations** (convolution, FFT, parallel compute)\n- ✅ **Experience with parallel tile computing** optimized for TT hardware\n- ✅ **Foundation for production applications** and model bring-up\n\n---\n\n## Next Step\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md#L107-L150","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cookbook-overview.md#L107-L150"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md","startLine":177,"endLine":226,"score":0.5653255119919777,"snippet":"│\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L177-L226","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L177-L226"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md","startLine":119,"endLine":166,"score":0.49859619140624994,"snippet":"learning_rate: 0.0001            # Standard for fine-tuning\n  weight_decay: 0.01\n  use_moreh_adamw: true\n  use_kahan_summation: false\n  use_clip_grad_norm: true\n  clip_grad_norm_max_norm: 1.0\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 4   # Effective batch: 8 * 4 = 32\n  eval_every: 50                   # Validate every 50 steps\n  model_save_interval: 100         # Checkpoint every 100 steps\n  tokenizer_type: \"bpe\"\n  checkpoint_dir: \"checkpoints\"\n  model_config: \"model_configs/model.yaml\"\n\n  # Logging configuration (tt-blacksmith pattern)\n  log_level: \"INFO\"\n  use_wandb: false                 # Optional experiment tracking\n  wandb_project: \"my-training\"\n  wandb_run_name: \"n150-experiment\"\n\n  # Checkpoi\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md#L119-L166","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct3-configuration-patterns.md#L119-L166"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md","startLine":737,"endLine":793,"score":0.4973596394062042,"snippet":"--model_path ~/tt-metal/tt-train/checkpoints/shakespeare_stage3.pkl_final.pkl \\\n  --max_new_tokens 50 \\\n  --temperature 0.8\n\n# Stage 4 (fluent!) - Expect high quality\npython train_nanogpt.py \\\n  --prompt \"ROMEO:\" \\\n  --model_path ~/tt-metal/tt-train/checkpoints/shakespeare_final.pkl_final.pkl \\\n  --max_new_tokens 50 \\\n  --temperature 0.8\n```\n\n**This demonstrates hierarchical learning visually!** 🎓\n\n---\n\n---\n\n## Step 8: Experiment with Temperature & Prompts 🎯\n\nNow that you have trained models, explore how temperature affects creativity!\n\n### Understanding Temperature\n\n**Temperature** controls output creativity:\n- **0.1** = Very deterministic (greedy-like, repetitive)\n- **0.5** = Balanced,\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md#L737-L793","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct4-finetuning-basics.md#L737-L793"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md","startLine":291,"endLine":351,"score":0.4792765527963638,"snippet":"- **Memory-bandwidth advantage**\n\n**This is why Tenstorrent is good at AI workloads** - lots of reuse of data in L1.\n\n---\n\n## Part 4: Hands-On - Measuring Memory Performance\n\nLet's write experiments to measure latency and bandwidth.\n\n### Experiment Setup\n\nWe'll create two programs:\n1. **Latency test:** Access single elements (worst case for cache)\n2. **Bandwidth test:** Access large sequential chunks (best case for cache)\n\n### Build the Memory Hierarchy Example\n\nFirst, let's build a custom example:\n\n```bash\ncd ~/tt-metal\n./build_metal.sh --build-programming-examples\n```\n\n[🔨 Build Examples](command:tenstorrent.buildProgrammingExamples)\n\n### Experiment 1: Latency - Random Access\n\n**Scenario:*\n\nSource: ../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L291-L351","source":"memory","citation":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/cs-fundamentals-02-memory.md#L291-L351"},{"path":"../../../code/tt-vscode-toolkit/content/lessons/ct5-multi-device-training.md","startLine":128,"endLine":199,"score":0.44390186965465545,"snippet":"- ⚠️ You only have N150 (single chip)\n- ⚠️ Debugging training issues (simpler to debug on 1 device)\n- ⚠️ Very small datasets (overhead not worth it)\n\n---\n\n## Configuration Changes for DDP\n\n### N150 (Single Device) - Baseline\n\n```yaml\ntraining_config:\n  batch_size: 8\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 4\n  # Effective batch: 8 × 4 = 32\n\ndevice_config:\n  enable_ddp: False\n  mesh_shape: [1, 1]               # 1 device\n```\n\n### N300 (Dual Chips) - DDP Enabled\n\n```yaml\ntraining_config:\n  batch_size: 16                   # 2x larger (split across devices)\n  gradient_accumulation_steps: 2   # Reduced (same effective batch)\n  # Effective batch: 16 × 2 = 32 (same as N150!)\n\ndevice_config:\n  enable_ddp: Tr\n\nSource: ../.